y&=4x^3+2\\
\Rightarrow\qquad \quad x&=4y^3+2\\

\Rightarrow\qquad 4y^3&=-x+2\\
\Rightarrow\qquad y^3&=-x/4+1/2\\
\Rightarrow\qquad y&=\sqrt[3]{-x/4+1/2}.
\end{align*}To find $f^{-1}(33)$, we set $y=33$: \begin{align*}
33&=\sqrt[3]{-\frac{x}{4}+\frac{1}{2}}\\
&=\sqrt[3]{-\frac{x}{4}+\frac{1\cdot2}{4}}\\
&=\sqrt[3]{-\frac{x}{4}+\frac{\cancel{1}\cdot2}{\cancel{4}}}\\
\Rightarrow\qquad \quad x&=-32\cdot4=-128.
\end{align*}Therefore, $f^{-1}(33)=\boxed{-128}.$

The way to find the inverse of a function $f(x)$ is to switch the roles of $x$ and $y$ (or $f(x)$) in the equation $y=f(x)$ and then solve the resulting equation for $x$, which will be the expression for $f^{-1}(x)$. In this case, if we let $y=4x^3+2$, then the $f^{-1}(x)$ will be solving the equation $x=4y^3+2$ for $y$. That is, let’s solve the equation \begin{align*}
x&=4y^3+2\\
\Rightarrow\qquad x-2&=4y^3\\
\Rightarrow\qquad y^3&=\frac{x-2}{4}\\
\Rightarrow\qquad y&=\sqrt[3]{\frac{x-2}{4}}\\
\Rightarrow\qquad f^{-1}(x)&=\sqrt[3]{\frac{x-2}{4}}
\end{align*}Finally, to find $f^{-1}(33)$, we just put in 33 in the formula for $f^{-1}(x)$: $$f^{-1}(33)=\sqrt[3]{\frac{33-2}{4}}=\sqrt[3]{\frac{31}{4}}\approx\boxed{2.5}.$$
